# Physical Layer Debugging (Start Here First)

Before checking software or configuration, always verify the physical layer.  
Most CAN failures originate from incorrect wiring, termination, or transceiver configuration.

---

## Basic CAN Hardware Setup

A typical CAN setup includes:
- Microcontroller
- CAN Controller (internal or external)
- CAN Transceiver (e.g., MCP2551, SN65HVD230)
- CAN Bus (CAN_H and CAN_L lines)
- Termination Resistors

## Basic Building Block
MCU ↔ CAN Controller ↔ CAN Transceiver ↔ CAN Bus ↔ Transceiver ↔ MCU

---

## CAN_H and CAN_L Wiring
### Symptoms of Wrong Wiring:
- No communication  
- Constant errors  
- Bus not responding  

### Common Mistakes:
- Swapped CAN_H and CAN_L  
- Loose connections  
- Missing common ground between nodes  

### Solution:
- Ensure CAN_H ↔ CAN_H and CAN_L ↔ CAN_L  
- Connect GND between all nodes  
- Use short and clean wiring for testing  

---

## Termination Resistors (Critical)
### Symptoms:
- Unstable communication  
- Random errors  
- Works sometimes, fails sometimes  

### Requirement:
- 120Ω resistor at **each end of the bus**
[120Ω] ---- CAN BUS ---- [120Ω]


### Common Mistakes:
- Missing termination  
- Only one resistor is used  
- Too many resistors  

### Solution:
- Place exactly two 120Ω resistors (at both ends)  
- Check the Resistance between CAN_H and CAN_L Bus, it should be between 45ohm to 65ohm.

---

## Slope Control (Rs Pin)

Many CAN transceivers (like MCP2551) use an **Rs pin** to control signal slope.

### What Rs Pin Does:
- Controls rise/fall time of CAN signals  
- Helps reduce EMI (electromagnetic interference)

### Common Configurations:
- **Rs connected to GND**
  - High-speed mode  
  - Fast signal edges  
  - Suitable for most applications  

- **Rs connected via resistor**
  - Slower edges  
  - Reduced EMI  
  - Used in noisy environments  

### Common Mistakes:
- Leaving Rs floating  
- Incorrect resistor value  

### Solution:
- For most setups, connect Rs directly to GND  
- Avoid floating pins  

---

## Power and Grounding
### Symptoms:
- Intermittent failures  
- Unstable communication  

### Common Issues:
- No shared ground  
- Power supply noise  

### Solution:
- Ensure all nodes share common ground  
- Use stable power supply  
- Add decoupling capacitors near transceiver  

---

## Quick Physical Layer Checklist
Before debugging software, verify:
- [ ] CAN_H and CAN_L correctly connected  
- [ ] Common ground shared  
- [ ] Two 120Ω termination resistors present  
- [ ] Rs pin properly configured (not floating)  
- [ ] Transceiver powered correctly  

